    <div class="container">
        <img class="biography-image desktopDisplay" src="img/vertical.jpg">
        <div class="biography-text">
            <p>
                Born in Washington, D.C. to a musical family, Leah Plave’s love for music and fine arts was encouraged from a young age. While living in D.C., she performed regularly with the Metropolitan Camerata, the Masterworks Festival Orchestra, and the Maryland Classic Youth Orchestra. She studied with National Symphony Orchestra cellist Mark Evans and kept a private studio of cello students ranging from young to adult musicians.
            </p>
            <p>
                Leah Plave attended The University of Cincinnati College- Conservatory of Music, where she studied with internationally acclaimed cellist Yehuda Hanani. During this time, she was a strings teacher at MYCincinnati, an El Sistema-inspired music program for youth in Cincinnati. She was also an active freelance musician in the Ohio area.
            </p>
            <p>
                Ms. Plave’s primary interest in chamber music has led her to participate in various music festivals, such as the Bowdoin International Music Festival and the Catskill High Peaks Festival. In 2014, she was an artist in residence at the Carey Institute for Global Good in New York during the Helderberg Chamber Music Series, and in 2015 she was one of 15 Young Artists to study and perform chamber music at the Manchester Music Festival.
            </p>
            <p>
                Leah Plave is currently an active recitalist, chamber musician, and teacher in Cincinnati. She will be pursuing her performance studies at the Liszt Academy of Music in Budapest, Hungary in 2015-2016.
            </p>
        </div>
